as someone living in poverty and unemployment to become socially active against those conditions? Their employment is indeed diverse - whether at the food banks, in counseling or in the protest against »the dole«. But the mechanisms of discrimination which act as barriers to these actors' claims for equality are also in effect in civil society. Leiv Eirik Voigtländer, with the help of qualitative interviews, analyses typical beneficial and inhibiting conditions of action, and thereby contributes to an understanding of the social division of civic action in the context of eroding social rights. The predominant focus on the civil apathy of the precarious is thus countered by the experiences of socially active citizens in situations of poverty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aArmut. 4aHartz IV. 4aPolitische Soziologie. 4aSoziale Bürgerrechte. 4aSoziale Ungleichheit. 4aSoziales Engagement. 4aSoziologie. 4aZivilgesellschaft. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh  aCivic Engagement.  aCivil Society.  aHartz IV.  aPolitical Sociology.  aPoverty.  aSocial Inequality.  aSocial Rights.  aSociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839431351zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839431351zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839431351/original  a978-3-11-070098-5 DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA